---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Articles', url: '/articles' },
  { name: 'Goat Kid Deposit and Sale Terms', url: '/articles/goat-kid-deposit-and-sale-terms' }
];

const lastReviewedISO = '2026-05-26';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: "Are goat-kid deposits typically refundable?",
    answer: "It depends entirely on the breeder's written contract. Most goat-kid deposit terms are non-refundable once the deposit secures a specific kid or a specific kidding window. Some breeders refund if the dam does not settle, does not produce a doeling/buckling of the requested sex, or does not produce a kid that meets the buyer's stated criteria. State pet-purchaser-protection statutes generally do not extend to livestock, so the contract controls. Read the refund clause before sending money."
  },
  {
    question: "When does title to a goat kid actually transfer to the buyer?",
    answer: "Two common patterns. Either at the moment of full payment (which can be at pickup, or before pickup if the kid is held for the buyer), or at the moment of pickup regardless of payment timing. The contract should state which. Title timing matters for insurance, for registry transfer paperwork, and for who bears the risk of loss between weaning and pickup."
  },
  {
    question: "What about registration transfer, ADGA, AGS, NDGA, MDGA?",
    answer: "Registration is a separate transaction from the sale. The breeder typically retains the registration application (or the registration certificate, if pre-registered) until full payment is received and the contract conditions are met. Some breeders condition registration transfer on the buyer following specific protocols (CDT vaccination, parasite-program participation, breeder review of the buyer's setup). The contract should state explicitly when the registration transfers and what would delay it."
  },
  {
    question: "Can a breeder hold a kid past weaning?",
    answer: `Yes, by agreement. "Hold-back" arrangements are common when the buyer needs more time or wants the breeder to handle disbudding, tattooing, CDT vaccination, and early weaning. A hold-back agreement should state the per-week board fee, what care is included, when title transfers, who bears veterinary costs during the hold, and what happens if pickup is missed.`
  },
  {
    question: "What does the breeder owe me at pickup?",
    answer: "At minimum, on a US goat sale: a bill of sale with the seller's scrapie premises ID, the kid's tattoo placement and characters, registration paperwork or registration application as appropriate to the contract, a vet-issued CVI if crossing state lines, the most recent disease-status testing certificates if attested, and a health record showing CDT vaccination dates, disbudding date, deworming history, and dam information. Anything less is incomplete."
  },
  {
    question: "How does breeder-buyer communication usually flow before pickup?",
    answer: "Established breeders typically send kidding updates (live birth, sex confirmation, weight at 24 hours, disbudding completion, weaning progress), invoice for any balance due, schedule pickup, and provide the documentation packet. Platforms like BreederHQ's buyer portal centralize this so buyers see updates, contracts, and payments in one place rather than scattered across text messages and email. Whether the breeder uses a platform or not, the buyer should expect proactive updates, having to chase a breeder for status is a meaningful signal about the program."
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Goat Kid Deposits & Sale Terms: What Breeders Put in Writing | BreederHQ"
  description="Goat kid deposit and sale terms: deposits, registration transfer, hold-backs, the CVI, and pickup docs. Know what a serious breeder puts in writing."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  faqs={faqs}
  article={{
    headline: "Goat Kid Deposit and Sale Terms: Deposits, Registration Transfer, Hold-Back Arrangements, and Pickup Documentation",
    description: "What to expect on the deposit, the registration transfer, the hold-back terms, and the documentation handoff when buying a goat kid.",
    datePublished: lastReviewedISO,
    dateModified: lastReviewedISO,
    author: {
      name: "BreederHQ Editorial"
    }
  }}
>
  <a href="#main-content" class="skip-link sr-only focus:not-sr-only focus:absolute focus:top-4 focus:left-4 focus:z-50 focus:px-4 focus:py-2 focus:bg-white focus:text-black focus:shadow-lg focus:rounded">
    Skip to content
  </a>

  <main id="main-content">
    <nav class="breadcrumb py-4 px-4 bg-gray-50" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <ol class="flex items-center space-x-2 max-w-4xl mx-auto text-sm">
        <li><a href="/" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">Home</a></li>
        <li class="text-gray-400">›</li>
        <li><a href="/articles" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">Articles</a></li>
        <li class="text-gray-400">›</li>
        <li aria-current="page" class="text-gray-600">Goat Kid Deposit and Sale Terms</li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <header class="pt-16 pb-8 px-4 bg-gradient-to-b from-stone-50 to-white">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mb-3">Buyer Guide · Goats</p>
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold tracking-tight text-gray-900 leading-tight mb-4">
          Goat Kid Deposit and Sale Terms: Deposits, Registration Transfer, Hold-Back Arrangements, and Pickup Documentation
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          Goat-kid sale terms look superficially like puppy-deposit terms but diverge on the things that actually matter, registration timing, scrapie compliance, hold-back arrangements through weaning, and the documentation packet expected at pickup. This guide breaks down what a buyer should expect to see in writing.
        </p>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-sm text-gray-500 border-t border-stone-200 pt-6">
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900">BreederHQ Editorial</p>
            <p>Updated May 2026</p>
          </div>
          <span class="text-gray-300">·</span>
          <p>May 26, 2026</p>
          <span class="text-gray-300">·</span>
          <p>11 min read</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <article class="pt-4 pb-12 px-4">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">The Deposit: Securing a Specific Kid vs a Future Kid</h2>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Goat-kid deposits typically secure one of two things. The first is a specific kid that has already been born, weighed, and sexed, you are reserving an identified animal at a fixed price. The second is a future kid from a planned kidding, sometimes with a sex preference and sometimes without. The deposit terms should state which.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Future-kid deposits usually include language for what happens if the dam does not settle, if the kidding does not produce the requested sex, or if no kid meets the buyer's stated criteria. Common outcomes: deposit rolls forward to the next kidding, deposit transfers to a different available kid, or deposit is refunded. The contract should pick one and be specific about the timeline.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            Refund terms for buyer-side cancellation are usually more restrictive. Most breeders write the deposit as non-refundable for buyer-initiated cancellation, because the breeder has held the kid (or held the pairing) and incurred opportunity cost. This is a normal industry pattern, not a red flag in itself. The red flag is a non-refundable deposit with no offsetting commitment to the buyer if the breeder cannot deliver.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Title Transfer: The Three Common Patterns</h2>

          <ol class="space-y-4 text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6 list-decimal pl-6">
            <li><strong>Title at full payment, pickup separately scheduled.</strong> Buyer pays in full, takes title, breeder boards the kid until pickup. The kid is the buyer's property during the hold, but the breeder is still responsible for routine care.</li>
            <li><strong>Title at pickup, regardless of payment timing.</strong> Even if the buyer has paid in full, title transfers when the kid is physically transferred. Risk of loss stays with the breeder until pickup. This is the more buyer-friendly pattern.</li>
            <li><strong>Title at registration transfer.</strong> Less common. Title is contingent on the breeder transferring registration paperwork to the buyer, which can be delayed by the buyer following stated protocols (vaccination, parasite-program participation).</li>
          </ol>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            None of these is universally correct. The contract just needs to say which one applies, and the buyer needs to understand what it means for insurance and risk during the period between payment and pickup.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Registration Transfer: ADGA, AGS, NDGA, MDGA</h2>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            For pedigreed dairy and meat goats, registration is its own transaction. ADGA (American Dairy Goat Association), AGS (American Goat Society), NDGA (Nigerian Dwarf Goat Association), and MDGA (Miniature Dairy Goat Association) all have their own registration forms, fees, and timing.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Common patterns: (a) the breeder pre-registers the kid in the breeder's herd name and transfers ownership to the buyer post-sale, (b) the breeder provides the registration application form signed but unfiled, leaving the buyer to file in their own herd name, or (c) the breeder transfers a completed certificate of registration with a transfer-of-ownership endorsement. Each has implications for fees, timing, and what name the kid is registered under.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            The contract should state which pattern applies, what the breeder pays for, what the buyer pays for, and what the buyer has to do to receive the registration paperwork. Conditioning registration transfer on the buyer following stated protocols (CDT vaccination, parasite-program participation) is legitimate but should be explicit.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Hold-Back: Boarding Through Weaning</h2>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Dairy-goat kids are typically weaned at 8 to 12 weeks; meat-goat kids vary. Buyers often want the breeder to handle disbudding (usually 4 to 10 days), CDT vaccination, tattooing, and weaning before pickup. That is a "hold-back" arrangement.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            A hold-back contract should state: the per-week or per-day board fee; what care is included (feed, hay, dewormer, routine vaccinations) and what is extra (vet visits, emergency care); when title transfers; who bears veterinary costs during the hold; what happens if pickup is missed (forfeiture of deposit, additional board fees, breeder's right to rehome). The hold-back is a meaningful chunk of the kid's early life, it deserves the same precision as the sale itself.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">The Pickup Documentation Packet</h2>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            At pickup, a serious breeder will hand the buyer a documentation packet that covers the regulatory, registry, and care-history sides of the kid. Expect:
          </p>

          <ul class="space-y-3 text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">
            <li class="flex items-start"><span class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mr-3 font-bold mt-1">•</span><span><strong>Bill of sale</strong> with the seller's scrapie premises ID and the kid's tattoo placement (right ear, left ear, tail web) and tattoo characters.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start"><span class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mr-3 font-bold mt-1">•</span><span><strong>Registration paperwork</strong> per the contract: certificate with transfer endorsement, registration application, or proof that registration is in process.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start"><span class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mr-3 font-bold mt-1">•</span><span><strong>CVI (Certificate of Veterinary Inspection)</strong> if the kid is moving across state lines.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start"><span class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mr-3 font-bold mt-1">•</span><span><strong>Disease-status certificates</strong> from the named lab (CAE, CL, Johne's) for the herd, with test dates and panels.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start"><span class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mr-3 font-bold mt-1">•</span><span><strong>Health record</strong> showing CDT vaccination dates, disbudding date, tattoo date, deworming history, and dam information.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start"><span class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mr-3 font-bold mt-1">•</span><span><strong>Pedigree</strong> for dairy goats, showing dam and sire LA scores and production records where relevant.</span></li>
            <li class="flex items-start"><span class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] mr-3 font-bold mt-1">•</span><span><strong>Contract</strong> signed by both parties, including any health guarantee terms.</span></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
            BreederHQ's sale-to-registry transfer-packet feature composes most of this into a single PDF, cover sheet, signed contracts, paid invoices, and offspring documentation, so the breeder can hand the buyer one consolidated artifact at pickup. The data underneath comes from the scheduled records, not from a free-text note.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Where BreederHQ Fits</h2>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            For breeders, the platform handles the deposit-through-pickup workflow as connected records: <a href="/workflows/kidding-management" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">kidding management</a>, deposit collection, invoice for balance, sale-to-registry transfer-packet generation, and the buyer portal for status updates. For buyers, the public marketplace surface shows the structured data, scrapie premises ID, tattoo placement, herd-health passport, parasite-program rollup, dairy production and Linear Appraisal for does, before the buyer inquires.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
            See the breeder-facing side at <a href="/articles/goat-herd-health-software" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">Goat Herd-Health Software</a> and <a href="/articles/dairy-goat-record-keeping-software" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">Dairy Goat Record-Keeping Software</a>. For the broader goat surface, see <a href="/goats" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">/goats</a>, and to weigh the platforms side by side, see our <a href="/compare/best-goat-breeding-software" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">goat breeding software comparison</a>.
          </p>

          <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed italic">
            This article is informational, not legal advice. Goat sale terms are governed by state contract law. State pet-purchaser-protection statutes generally do not extend to livestock. Consult a local attorney for legal questions about a specific contract.
          </p>
        </section>

      </div>
    </article>

    <section class="py-16 px-4 bg-gray-50">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-6">
          {faqs.map((faq) => (
            <details class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-6 group">
              <summary class="font-semibold text-lg text-gray-900 cursor-pointer flex items-center justify-between">
                <span>{faq.question}</span>
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">{faq.answer}</p>
            </details>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <style>
    .sr-only {
      position: absolute;
      width: 1px;
      height: 1px;
      padding: 0;
      margin: -1px;
      overflow: hidden;
      clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
      white-space: nowrap;
      border-width: 0;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
